==English==

=== Etymology ===

From Old English bycgan, that means ''obtain by paying a price''. This word does not come from Gothic [[bugjan]], which is a frequent false assumpttion. Both are cognate, i.e. both represent the same proto-indo-european root [[*bheug(h)]], related to the meaning of [[freedom]], and existed in parallel in different Germanic dialects. This evolution is explained by original meaning of the word bugjan, strictly related to the commerce of slaves. When buying a slave, the buyer was granting him some rights he didn't have when he were for sale, thus freeing him. In viking the form is byggja.

